		   <table class=mform2  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
		   <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform2 valign=top>
		   
		   <span class=sm>Posted @ Tue, Oct 14th 8:10 AM 2003 </span><span id=notbold>| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a class=sm href="classes2.html?class=8&mid=10660067232548&post=1&replyto=106613255260499"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=106613255260499></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform2>
		   <span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=151942"><span id=Guru>Kelanthor</span></a><b><span id=Guru><br>Guru</span></b><br><img src=/shared/user_star_ico.gif height=9 width=9><br>167 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</nobr>
		   <br><img src=/shared/transp.gif width=135 border=0 height=1></td><td valign=top class=mform2 width=100%><p>Greetings,<br><br>The traditional route for fast experience today seems to be to hit Paludal Caverns as soon as you can, and stay there until the early 20s.<br><br>As far as tradeskills go, I'd recommend tailoring. <img border=0 src=/shared/smilies/grin.gif><br><br>Now, this trade will make you mad, <img border=0 src=/shared/smilies/mad.gif><br>make you want to bang your head off your desk, <img border=0 src=/shared/smilies/banghead.gif><br>but you should find it ultimately rewarding. <img border=0 src=/shared/smilies/yippee.gif><br><br>Getting started is easy - save all the pelts, hides and silks you come across, then check www.eqtraders.com to see how you can use them. If you do decide on tailoring, then you'll probably end up doing a bit of brewing and blacksmithing to support your main skill. The advantage of tailoring is that you can actually make things you can wear from the start - and you'll come across useful items like bags, backpacks and quivers as you go along that you can sell.<br><br>Other good choices would be baking or brewing, as you can use a lot of the stuff you forage in recipes in both of these skills. Fishing, while not that useful, you can advance in your down time if you sit by a body of water while medding and keep your pole and bait with you. The fish you catch can again be used to advance baking. If you do decide on tailoring, you'll end up fishing anyway, as when you get on a bit in skill levels, you'll need Cobalt Cod to make a tannin for those Velious leather armours.<br><br>Best thing to do is maybe try out all skills to a low level and see which one you prefer. Easiest to advance are probably brewing and baking - you can go to 248 brewing and 191 baking purely on storebought items. The two hardest (and probably most expensive) are blacksmithing and tailoring. However, if you persevere, you can make money at these, but it does take patience!<br><br>Hope this helps.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Oct 17 05:25:35 2003</em></p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Kelanthor<br>Wood Elf Wanderer of the 53rd Circle<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672</a><br>"It's only the giving that makes you what you are..."</td></td></tr>
